Course Summary

Increase your confidence prior to sitting for the Praxis Mathematics exam by making use of the video lessons and quizzes in this course. You can access this study guide, which highlights the topics that may appear on the exam, and its comprehensive tools at any time as you prepare for the exam.

About This Course

Get ready to take the Praxis Mathematics Content Knowledge exam with help from this study guide course. All of the subjects you'll need to know to do well on this test are presented in a series of engaging lessons. They address such topics as algebraic equations and expressions, asymptotes, complex numbers, inverse functions and more. Help from one of our experts is available through the Dashboard if you find that you need assistance with these concepts.

Check out our Praxis Preparation resources! We've got Praxis courses to teach you the material, comprehensive Praxis study guides to help you study, Praxis practice tests to test your knowledge, and Praxis informational articles to get you up to speed on testing logistics.

Syllabus & Course Information

To help you prepare for the Praxis math test, we have developed a series of online video lessons. These resources teach you about algebraic expressions, equations, formulas and fractions via mobile device or computer. After finishing this course, you should be able to do the following:

  • Understand approximating and averaging
  • Define congruence and similarity
  • Discuss derivatives
  • Explain the concept of graphing
  • Detail matrices
  • Outline systems of equations
  • Identify trigonometric functions
  • Define volume in math

Course Format

Our test prep course is made up of 309 lessons grouped into 47 chapters for your review. Before you take the test, answer the questions on the lesson quizzes and chapter tests to see if you're ready and where you need to study further.

Praxis Mathematics - Content Knowledge Exam Information

To work as a public high school math teacher in the majority of the country, you'll need to pass the Praxis Mathematics: Content Knowledge test. This exam is intended for those who have completed, or are about to complete, an appropriate bachelor's degree program.

  • Number of Questions: 60
  • Question Type: selected-response, numeric entry, text completion and drag-and-drop questions
  • Time Limit: 150 minutes
  • Exam Cost: $120

Praxis Mathematics: Content Knowledge Test Preparation & Registration

You can refresh your math skills in preparation for the Praxis by completing our chapter on mathematics. Our brief video lessons are led by experienced educators, and the quizzes that accompany each lesson not only test your knowledge of math, but they also expose you to the types of questions you'll encounter come test day.

The Praxis Mathematics Content Knowledge test is offered via computer several times a year; you can find specific dates on the ETS website. The test also can be taken four times per year in a paper-based format. Registration for both forms of the test is possible online, by phone or via mail; registration for the paper-delivered test ends approximately one month before the test date.

Be sure you arrive at the testing center on time (30 minutes prior to test time is recommended for those taking the computer-based test). You'll need to bring your admission ticket, a photo ID and, if you're taking the paper-based test, several sharpened No. 2 pencils. You also should bring a graphing calculator; please note that test administrators are required to clear the memory of your calculator before and after you take the Praxis math test.

Praxis Mathematics: Content Knowledge Test Scoring

Scores are available via phone and online approximately two to three weeks after the computer-based test or around three weeks after the paper-based test. Your scores also will be sent to as many as three licensing agencies or institutions, which you can choose during the registration process.

The minimum score needed to pass the Praxis Mathematics Content Knowledge test, and thus qualify for teacher certification, is set by each individual state that uses the exam. In addition to noting your total score, your score report will give you a breakdown of how well you performed in each of the content areas on the Praxis, which include the following:

Algebra and Number Theory

One of the largest content areas on the Praxis Mathematics Content Knowledge test, algebra and number theory comprises approximately 16% of all questions. This section might test your knowledge of complex numbers systems or your ability to solve problems that involve ratios or percentages. You also might be asked to graph inequalities or use algebraic representations of spheres or planes.

Measurement

In the section on measurement, you'll be asked about appropriate units of measure, and you might have to analyze precision and accuracy in measuring situations. Other topics covered in this content category, which makes up around 6% of the test, include limits in measurement and successive approximation.

Geometry

The geometry section of the Praxis covers topics like congruence and similarity and the Pythagorean theorem. You'll need to know the properties of various shapes, including triangles, circles, parallelograms and trapezoids, and be able to solve problems based on these properties. This content category accounts for approximately 10% of the Praxis math exam.

Trigonometry

This section features around 8% of the questions on the test and measures your knowledge of the six basic trigonometric functions. You might be asked about the laws of sines and cosines, and you're expected to know how to convert between rectangular and polar coordinate systems.

Functions

Another 16% of the Praxis math test focuses on functions. For this section of the exam, you'll need to know about domain and range, asymptotes and discontinuities. You might be asked to determine the inverse of a function or interpret a 3-dimensional graph. You'll also need to understand the properties of various types of functions, including exponential, polynomial and rational.

Calculus

Questions on calculus comprise approximately 12% of this exam. In this section, you might be asked to determine limits of a function or approximate integrals and derivatives. Other topics that might be covered include the mean value theorem and the fundamental theorem of calculus.

Data Analysis and Statistics

This section of the test measures your proficiency at organizing, describing, comparing and analyzing data. You'll be expected to know what constitutes a well-designed study, as well as determine appropriate measures of central tendency. This category accounts for 10-12% of the questions on the Praxis.

Probability

Approximately 4-6% of questions on the Praxis cover probability. You might be required to demonstrate your understanding of sample space or determine the expected value of a random variable. Other topics covered in this section might include probability distribution, conditional probability and independent events.

Matrix Algebra

Questions on matrix algebra make up around 8-10% of the Praxis math test. For this exam section, you'll need to know about vectors and matrices, including how to add, subtract, multiply and divide them. Additionally, you might be asked to represent translations and dilations of objects in a plane using vectors and matrices, as well as sketches and coordinates.

Discrete Mathematics

The final section of the Praxis focuses on discrete mathematics. This category makes up approximately 6-8% of the exam. Questions might center on permutations and combinations, discrete and continuous representations, or types of binary relations. You also might have to model simple phenomena, such as compound interest, using finite and infinite math.
